Project: TMDb Movie Data Analysis¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

In this project, I will be analysing data of about 10,000 movies having user ratings, revenue, budget and genre among other columns. From 1960 to 2015, the data set has quite extensive information on Hollywood movies(only US).

I will try to explore what makes a movie successful and what makes a movie a failure. I will specifically analyse successful movies' trends comparing to unsuccessful movies to make informed and precise conclusions.

Questions I hope to be asking and answering are:

  • Are certain genres more profitable than others? And if so, which ones? And how to classify them?
  • How about actors, is there a way to know if having many stars in a one movie a guarantee to success?
  • How have genres evolved through time?
  • Which companies make the most? Do they also invest more money? Do they make ROIs depending on genres?

Data Cleaning (Dropping empty rows and splitting columns)¶

The data set has many missing values(some more important, others not), I will spend some time cleaning mostly zero budget and zero revenue rows since those are important errors I can't proceed with.

Next, I will separate the multi-row-combined genres, and do the same thing for the production companies, so that I may explore each individually later on.

Conclusions¶

Many of the conclusions to be made here are difficult because this data set is mostly qualitative than quantitative. Those are limitations of this data set. If the data set included popularity rates for each actor and director, I would explore more the relationship between an actor, a production company, a director and a story line; I think it's where the secret lies when it comes to movies.

Another limitation I have to mention is the fact that I deleted thousands of rows (of empty budget and/or revenue), which may or may not make my findings biased (in successful vs failed movies categories) since most of the deleted rows lied in the failed category.

Generally speaking, with the data set at hand, I saw that a movie could be successful a year and a similar movie the next year would fail. There are no clear patters or clear conclusion to be made. Not to say that there is no insight from this data, but they are more recommendations or such. For example, if I were to recommend something to a hollywood company based on this data, I would say:

  • Invest (talking about a budget) something more but not too much either; as I saw that successful movies lie in the mid budget zone.
  • Consinder genres like action, romance, thriller and science fiction; as they keep getting popular.
  • Consinder a big cast than a small one; the large ones tend to be more and more successful.
  • Don't make hiring a star a priority, they are not a guarantee for a movie to succeed or not.
  • Having a movie over 100 minutes but not over 115 minutes can prove important in a success of a movie.
